06859nam a22009135i 9780300171617DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20102010ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803001716177 a10.12987/97803001716172doi  a(DE-B1597)486126  a(OCoLC)1059251873  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 4aBJ320 7aPHI0050002bisacsh04a17003aAn Ethical Compass :bComing of Age in the 21st Century. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[2010] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (400 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1986, Elie Wiesel received the Nobel Peace Prize in recognition of his victory over “the powers of death and degradation, and to support the struggle of good against evil in the world.” Soon after, he and his wife, Marion, created the Elie Wiesel Foundation for Humanity. A project at the heart of the Foundation’s mission is its Ethics Prize-a remarkable essay-writing contest through which thousands of students from colleges across the country are encouraged to confront ethical issues of personal significance. The Ethics Prize has grown exponentially over the past twenty years.“Of all the projects our Foundation has been involved in, none has been more exciting than this opportunity to inspire young students to examine the ethical aspect of what they have learned in their personal lives and from their teachers in the classroom,” writes Elie Wiesel. Readers will find essays on Bosnia, the genocide in Rwanda, sweatshops and globalization, and the political obligations of the mothers of Argentina’s Disappeared. Other essays tell of a white student who joins a black gospel choir, a young woman who learns to share in Ladakh, and the outsize implications of reporting on something as small as a cracked windshield. Readers will be fascinated by the ways in which essays on conflict, conscience, memory, illness (Rachel Maddow’s essay on AIDS appears), and God overlap and resonate with one another.These essays reflect those who are “sensitive to the sufferings and defects that confront a society yearning for guidance and eager to hear ethical voices,” writes Elie Wiesel. “And they are a beacon for what our schools must realize as an essential component of a true education.”  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aEthics, Moderny21st century. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Ethics & Moral Philosophy.2bisacsh1 aAtkins, Zohar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarnard, Leslie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBender, Kimlyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrkic, Courtney, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrophy, Peggy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDaley, Kelly A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuker, Tamara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFriedman, Thomas L.1 aFriedman, Thomas L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGibson, Mae, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHalabi, Sami F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHandler, Allison, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHo, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKe, Tracy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKolbi-Molinas, Alexa R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKupperman, Kim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLong, James D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.